observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:

The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System;

The Municipal Treasurer/General Services Officer to render a report on Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period, to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;

The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant (MA) the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same to the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year; and

The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive shall create an Inventory Committee:

Which will devote time and attention to fast track the conduct of a complete physical inventory of all the property of the Municipality;

Assign a unique property number for each PPE item following the required code format in the numbering system stated in the Circular;

Prepare a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and submit the same to the COA Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;

Prepare an Inventory Count Form which will serve as basis in the preparation of RPCPPE after the physical count;

Prepare a List of PPEs Found at Station and List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs during the physical inventory to establish the existence and proper accountability of the PPE accounts; and

Observe the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE as provided in COA Circular 2020-006 to facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

Further, the LCE direct the MA to prepare the necessary correcting entry to reclassify the PPE accounts amounting to ₱1.43 million, taking into consideration the capitalization threshold of ₱15,000 for recognition as PPE.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Treasurer:

To identify the specific sources of funds and establish whether these were essentially idle funds in accordance with Section 21 and 22 of COA Circular No. 92-382. In cases when there are idle funds identified, investing such should have prior authority of the Sanggunian and the approval of the Local Chief Executive;

To transfer the amount of ₱353,219 to the Municipality’s Current Account maintained for Trust Funds and hasten the implementation of the programs, projects and activities for which the fund was created/intended for; and

To secure a copy of the passbook/bank statement to determine the transactions that occurred during the period of transition from PSB to LBP and provide the MA the relevant information thereon to properly account for the unrecorded transactions; 

Further, we recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the balances of the Cash-in Bank, LCCA, Time Deposit in their respective records to reflect the correct figures in the financial statements.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:
The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System;
The Municipal Treasurer/General Services Officer to render a report on Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
The Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same to the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year; and
The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the LCE require:
The comprehensive coordination between the offices of GAD Focal, MPDO and Budget for the complete and accurate reporting of GAD plans and budget and accomplishment report;
That changes in the plan/budget shall be approved by authorized officials through a resolution, supported with revised GPB, reviewed and approved by the DILG Provincial Office;
The proper and consistent identification of the PPAs, whether beneficiaries are properly targeted, identified and prioritized in order to correctly and systematically assess and identify its effectivenes; and
Remind the MPDO/GAD Focal Person that any changes in the approved GAD budget be supported with revised GPB, indorsed by the SB and reviewed and approved by the DILG Provincial Office.
We also recommend that Management revisit their programs/projects, give more attention and study on how to maximize the utilization of the GAD budget through the implementation of GAD related programs and projects in order to attain the objective for which the fund were provided.

We recommended that Management direct the concerned officials/employees the immediate compliance of the following:
Provide the required site record at Sanitary Landfills;
Full implementation of no segregation, no collection policy specifically in barangays outside Poblacion;
Conduct monitoring and remind barangays on the establishment of MRF;
Enforce the establishment of composting area within the temporary municipal sanitary land fill;
Instruct proper maintenance of the temporary dump site and provide all the required necessities.
Monitor the status of the construction of sanitary land fill and enforce the necessary action for its complete implementation.
Further, we reiterated our prior year’s recommendation to conduct strict monitoring of areas in the Municipality where indiscriminate dumping of wastes is observed and enforce regulations, including imposition of penalties for non-compliance.

We recommended that Management direct:
The Municipal Budget Office to follow the required format in preparing the SAAOB by presenting in detail the functions, programs, projects and activities pertaining to the Senior Citizen and the PWD;
The Municipal Accounting Office to maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for Senior Citizen and  PWD;
The regular reconcilation of balances between the Budget and Accounting offices to ensure consistency, accuracy, and completeness of financial records; and
The OSCA and MSWD offices to prepare complete and detailed plan/budget and accomplishment reports for the the Senior Citizen and PWD PPAs and reconcile such data/information with the Municipal Budget and Accounting offices.

We recommended that Management:

Prepare and issue demand letters to concerned officers and employees with outstanding cash advances requiring them to immediately settle their unliquidated cash advances;

Cause or order the withholding of the payment of any amount due the officers or employees concerned with unliquidated cash advances as provided by paragraph 9.3.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 in case of failure to settle their cash advances after demand has been made; 

Prepare a Request for Authority to Write-off the dormant receivable accounts amounting to ₱90,310.26 following the procedures provided in Sections 8.2 and 8.3  of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that cash donations are properly acknowledged through the issuance of official receipt and deposited in the AGDB of the LGU, and strictly observe the guidelines in the utilizations thereof in accordance with COA Circular No. 2014-002;

Require the concerned personnel to submit the required supporting documents on the utilization of cash donation of ₱100,000.00 to prevent the issuance of Notice of Suspension or Notice of Disallowance, if warranted. 

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to open a separate bank account for Trust Fund-DRRMF in the LGU’s Authorized Government Depository Bank and transfer DRRMF cash donations to that account. Henceforth, to ensure that cash donations received by the Municipality are deposited therein;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain separate Subsidiary Ledgers for Trust Liabilities-DRRM,  for cash donations received amounting to ₱100,000 and above per donor per purpose while those below ₱100,000 shall be grouped and posted in one SL labeled as “Various Donors” per purpose; and

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain Registry of Cash Donation and Utilization.

